<!-- coder-team.archml — PARALLEL SUB-AGENTS: a lead agent that spawns background sub-agents
     (agent-loop.md §16, "a background job can be another <m-agent>"). This is the async
     job registry (milestone 6) turned on its most interesting payoff: a background job need
     not be a shell command — it can be a whole other agent, running its own tool-calling
     loop. The lead breaks a task into independent pieces, hands each to a background worker
     with spawn_agent, keeps going while they run, and collects results with check/wait —
     and is NOTIFIED when each finishes. The loop stays synchronous and deterministic; only
     the TOOLS are async-shaped (§16, "async agency without an async loop").

     Run:
       MEDITATOR_OBJECTIVE="…a task with independent pieces…" \
         bun meditator.js -a architecture/agents/coder-team.archml
     Ctrl-C sleeps the lead and every worker gracefully (and kills any running job).

     NOTE (local models): both the lead's and each worker's m-reason call the model WITH
     tools, so a local vLLM must be launched with --enable-auto-tool-choice and a matching
     --tool-call-parser (agent-loop.md §12). Sub-agent jobs need no sandbox themselves (a
     job is a loop), but the workers' terminals do. -->
<m-agent name="lead"
         interlocutor="user"
         model="voice"
         utilityModel="utility"
         maxSteps="80"
         stopWhen="no-tools">
  You are the LEAD of a small team of coding agents, working in a sandboxed workspace. Given
  a task, first size it up. When it splits into independent pieces that can proceed at the
  same time, hand each piece to a background sub-agent with spawn_agent — then keep working
  (plan the next piece, read code, prepare the integration) while they run. Poll a job with
  check, block on one with wait when you have nothing else to do, and you will also be told
  when a job finishes. A sub-agent runs one task at a time, so to run two pieces at once,
  give them to two different workers. Only claim the whole task is done once you have
  collected and verified every sub-agent's result. When it is complete, reply with a short
  summary and no tool call.

  <!-- The seed of the WORK — overridable at wake with MEDITATOR_OBJECTIVE. -->
  <m-objective name="objective">
    Split the work into independent pieces, run them in parallel with the workers, then
    integrate and verify the result.
  </m-objective>

  <!-- The lead's own reasoner. Declared FIRST so `reason/reply` (a name-based ref) resolves
       to it and not to a worker's identically-named reasoner (refs are position-relative;
       first in document order wins). -->
  <m-reason name="reason" toolTokens="2048" temperature="0.2"></m-reason>

  <!-- The lead's own light belt: read/plan/integrate. Heavy work goes to the workers. -->
  <m-read-file  name="read_file"></m-read-file>
  <m-write-file name="write_file"></m-write-file>
  <m-edit       name="edit"></m-edit>

  <!-- The BACKGROUND SUB-AGENTS (agent-loop.md §16). Each is a full agent: role="subagent"
       makes it private — it does not auto-begin or take tasks over a membrane; it idles
       until the lead spawns it as a job. Its own tools (terminal, file tools) register with
       IT, not the lead — the nearest entity owns its tools — and it shares the workspace, so
       a file one worker writes is visible to the others and to the lead. Two workers so two
       pieces can genuinely run at once; add more for wider fan-out. -->
  <m-agent name="worker-a" role="subagent" maxSteps="30" stopWhen="finish-tool">
    You are a worker agent. Given a concrete, self-contained task, carry it out in the shared
    workspace: write code, run it, read what came back, and loop until it is genuinely done
    and checked. Prefer small, verified steps. Never claim something works until you have run
    it and seen it. Call finish(summary) with a short, plain account of what you did or found.

    <m-reason name="reason" toolTokens="2048" temperature="0.2"></m-reason>
    <m-terminal   name="terminal"   wall="120s" network="off"></m-terminal>
    <m-read-file  name="read_file"></m-read-file>
    <m-write-file name="write_file"></m-write-file>
    <m-edit       name="edit"></m-edit>
    <m-repeat-guard nudgeAt="3" haltAt="6"></m-repeat-guard>
  </m-agent>

  <m-agent name="worker-b" role="subagent" maxSteps="30" stopWhen="finish-tool">
    You are a worker agent. Given a concrete, self-contained task, carry it out in the shared
    workspace: write code, run it, read what came back, and loop until it is genuinely done
    and checked. Prefer small, verified steps. Never claim something works until you have run
    it and seen it. Call finish(summary) with a short, plain account of what you did or found.

    <m-reason name="reason" toolTokens="2048" temperature="0.2"></m-reason>
    <m-terminal   name="terminal"   wall="120s" network="off"></m-terminal>
    <m-read-file  name="read_file"></m-read-file>
    <m-write-file name="write_file"></m-write-file>
    <m-edit       name="edit"></m-edit>
    <m-repeat-guard nudgeAt="3" haltAt="6"></m-repeat-guard>
  </m-agent>

  <!-- ASYNC AGENCY (agent-loop.md §16). It discovers the two workers above and offers
       spawn_agent(agent, task) alongside spawn / check / wait / kill / list_jobs — sub-agent
       jobs live in the SAME registry as shell jobs, so the same tools collect both. One
       line, no core change. -->
  <m-jobs name="jobs" wall="10m" network="off"></m-jobs>

  <!-- Stall guard for the lead itself (agent-loop.md §9). Each worker has its own. -->
  <m-repeat-guard nudgeAt="3" haltAt="8"></m-repeat-guard>

  <!-- To work on a real project, give every file/terminal/jobs tool the same root=, e.g.
         <m-read-file name="read_file" root="/path/to/project"></m-read-file>
       To watch it in the Studio, add <m-ws name="ws" port="7643"></m-ws>. -->
</m-agent>
